GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 3
HOUSE BILL 162
Senate Agriculture, Energy, and Environment Committee Substitute Adopted 6/17/26
Third Edition Engrossed 6/23/26
Short Title: Parking Lot Reform/Stormwater Control. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
February 24, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO RESTRICT LOCAL GOVERNMENTS FROM REGULATING CERTAIN
3 ASPECTS OF OFF-STREET PARKING SPACES AND TO MODIFY THE AUTHORITY
4 OF CERTAIN LOCAL GOVERNMENTS TO REQUIRE STORMWATER CONTROL
5 FOR REDEVELOPED PROPERTY.
6 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
7
8 PART I. PROHIBITING CERTAIN ZONING AND DEVELOPMENT LIMITATIONS
9 RELATED TO OFF-STREET PARKING
10 SECTION 1.(a) G.S. 160D-702 reads as rewritten:
11 "§ 160D-702. Grant of power.
12 …
13 (c) A zoning or other development regulation shall not do any of the following:
14 (1) Set a minimum square footage of any structures subject to regulation under
15 the North Carolina Residential Code.
16 (2) Require a an off-street parking space to be larger than 9 feet wide by 20 feet
17 long unless the parking space is designated for handicap, parallel, or diagonal
18 parking.
19 (2a) Require an off-street parking lot to meet a minimum number of parking spaces
20 per development or structure, regardless of occupancy or use. The limitations
21 of this subdivision shall not, however, apply to local governments located in
22 the coastal area, as those terms are defined under G.S. 113A-103, except with
23 respect to the following properties located in the coastal area:
24 a. Within the boundaries of a National Register Historic District or a
25 local historic district.
26 b. That are either (i) individually listed in the National Register of
27 Historic Places or (ii) individually designated as a local historic
28 landmark.
29 c. Individual properties on the Study List for the National Register of
30 Historic Places as maintained by the North Carolina State Historic
31 Preservation Office or a national or State historic landmark, or
32 properties located within a district on the Study List for the National
33 Register of Historic Places as maintained by the North Carolina State
34 Historic Preservation Office or a national or State historic landmark.
*H162-v-3*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) Require additional fire apparatus access roads into developments of one- or
2 two-family dwellings that are not in compliance with the required number of
3 fire apparatus access roads into developments of one- or two-family dwellings
4 set forth in the Fire Code of the North Carolina Residential Code for One- and
5 Two-Family Dwellings.
6 (4) Establish or require pavement design standards for public roads or private
7 roads that are more stringent than the minimum pavement design standards
8 adopted by the Department of Transportation.
9 …."
10 SECTION 1.(b) This section becomes effective January 1, 2027.
11
12 PART II. MODIFY THE AUTHORITY OF CERTAIN LOCAL GOVERNMENTS TO
13 REQUIRE STORMWATER CONTROL FOR REDEVELOPED PROPERTY
14 SECTION 2.(a) G.S. 143-214.7 reads as rewritten:
15 "§ 143-214.7. Stormwater runoff rules and programs.
16 …
17 (a1) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
18 (1) Built-upon area. – As defined in G.S. 143-214.7D.
19 (2) Development. – Any land-disturbing activity that increases the amount of
20 built-upon area or that otherwise decreases the infiltration of precipitation into
21 the subsoil. When additional development occurs at a site that has existing
22 development, the built-upon area of the existing development shall not be
23 included in the density calculations for additional stormwater control
24 requirements, and stormwater control requirements cannot be applied
25 retroactively to existing development, unless otherwise required by federal
26 law.
27 (2)(3) Redevelopment. – Any land-disturbing activity that does not result in a net
28 increase in built-upon area and that provides greater or equal stormwater
29 control to that of the previous development.
30 …
31 (b3) Stormwater runoff rules and programs shall not require private property owners to
32 install new or increased stormwater controls for (i) preexisting development existing built-upon
33 area or (ii) redevelopment activities that do not remove or decrease existing stormwater controls.
34 When a preexisting development is redeveloped, either in whole or in part, increased stormwater
35 controls shall only be required for the amount of impervious surface being created that exceeds
36 the amount of impervious surface that existed before the redevelopment, irrespective of whether
37 the impervious surface that existed before the redevelopment is to be demolished or relocated
38 during the development activity. When development or redevelopment occurs at a site that has
39 existing built-upon area, (i) the existing built-upon area shall not be included in the density
40 calculations for additional stormwater control requirements, irrespective of whether the existing
41 built-upon area is to be demolished, relocated, replaced, or remains in place during development
42 activity, (ii) the existing built-upon area at the site is not subject to additional stormwater control
43 requirements under this section, regardless of whether the existing built-upon area is demolished,
44 relocated, replaced, or remains in place during the development activity, (iii) for purposes of
45 determining the size of the area for which stormwater control measures are required for a
46 development or redevelopment, built-upon area that existed before the development or
47 redevelopment shall be applied on a square-foot-for-square-foot basis to reduce the built-upon
48 area for which stormwater control measures are required, and (iv) stormwater control
49 requirements cannot be applied retroactively to existing built-upon area, unless otherwise
50 required by federal law. A property owner may elect to treat the stormwater resulting from the
51 net increase in built-upon area above the preexisting existing built-upon area at the development
